# Task logging

Every task you complete must be logged to the Revex brain so the team has visibility into work patterns, time spent, and friction.

## Protocol

### Step 1 — at the START of every task (before any other work)

Run this exactly once, the moment a user prompt begins:

```bash
./scripts/log-task.sh start "ONE_SENTENCE_TASK_SUMMARY"
```

Where `ONE_SENTENCE_TASK_SUMMARY` is what the user asked for, in their words where possible. Examples:
- "Add image attachment support to the Slack bot"
- "Fix the auth flow redirect after sign-out"
- "Implement dark mode toggle"

### Step 2 — at the END of every task (before your final response to the user)

Run this exactly once, when the task is complete (success, failure, or abandoned):

```bash
./scripts/log-task.sh end "ONE_SENTENCE_TASK_SUMMARY" "COMPLICATIONS"
```

`COMPLICATIONS` is a self-report of anything that went wrong, required multiple attempts, caused errors, or was unexpectedly complex. Be specific. Future sessions read this to avoid the same pitfalls. Examples:
- `"none"` — task completed without issues
- `"Circular dependency required lazy dynamic import to resolve"`
- `"Type error in LLMContentBlock required rebuilding @revex/core before tsc would pass"`
- `"Merge conflict — main had already committed feature X"`

## Rules

- Run `start` exactly once per user prompt, before anything else.
- Run `end` exactly once per user prompt, immediately before your final response.
- One log entry per user request — not per file edit.
- If a task is abandoned, still call `end` with `"Abandoned because <reason>"` as complications.
- Never skip these calls. The log is used for time estimation, team activity dashboards, and learning from past hurdles.
- If the script fails or `REVEX_TASK_LOG_KEY` isn't set, the script exits silently — do not retry, do not block work.

## Why two calls instead of one

Without a `start` call, the brain has no way to measure duration. Cursor doesn't have shell hooks like Claude Code does, so the AI itself is responsible for capturing both timestamps.
